article.description: Morris Peterson scored a career-high 31 points and Vince Carter added 23 in his first start since Nov. 2 as the Toronto Raptors snapped a six-game losing streak with a 98-95 victory over the Boston Celtics on Friday night.

related.description: Vince Carter is back, but the Raptors could also use a strong dose of defense and rebounding.

article.headline: Peterson pulls Raptors out of six-game slide
article.linkText: Raptors outlast Celtics to end six-game skid
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- On a night when the attention was focused on Vince Carter's return to the starting lineup, Toronto Raptors teammate Morris Peterson caught the Celtics by surprise.
Carter

Peterson

Carter scored 23 points in his first start since Nov. 2, but it was Peterson's career-high 31 points that sparked the Raptors to a 98-95 victory over Boston on Friday night, snapping Toronto's six-game losing streak. "Most definitely, having Vince back helps. It kind of takes a load off,'' said Peterson, who shot 12-of-18 from the field after shooting 17-for-64 in the previous four games. Of his struggles, Peterson said: "I was pressing a little bit, trying to do too much, instead of letting the game come to me. Tonight I made up my mind to let the game come to me. I played hard tonight and the shots began to fall.'' It was Carter's second game back after missing the team's previous 10 with a strained quadriceps muscle in his left knee. In Wednesday night's loss to the Wizards, he scored 16 points and had seven rebounds in 24 minutes; on Friday night, he scored 16 in the first quarter. "We wanted him to get his feet wet, so to speak, and he came out stronger (tonight),'' said Raptors coach Lenny Wilkens. "Every guy out there feels a little better with him on the floor.'' Antoine Walker tied a season high with 31 points for the Celtics, who had won four straight. Antonio Davis gave the Raptors a 90-83 lead with 7:14 left, but the Celtics scored six straight points -- including four by Tony Battie -- to cut it to 90-89. The Raptors went ahead 94-90, but Walker's free throws cut it to 94-92. Davis, who had 13 points, knocked down two free throws to put the Raptors up 96-92, but Walker hit a fallaway 3-pointer with 10.9 seconds left to cut the lead to 96-95. Alvin Williams hit two free throws with 8.9 seconds left to seal the victory. Williams had 11 assists. Paul Pierce added 16 points and 10 rebounds for Boston. Battie scored 15 and Shammond Williams added 11. "We had some good looks, they just didn't fall tonight,'' Pierce said. "It's a tough loss for us and we know we didn't play our best game, but that's what the NBA is all about. You have to be ready to bounce back.'' Peterson scored 11 points in the first six minutes of the third quarter as the Raptors took a 12-point lead, but the Celtics used a 16-2 run -- highlighted by Shammond Williams' 3-pointer and Battie's dunk -- to take a 78-76 lead. Peterson hit a jumper at the third-quarter buzzer to tie it. Carter helped the Raptors to a 32-24 first quarter lead, but he was held scoreless the rest of the half as the Celtics used a 19-6 run in the second quarter to take a 50-49 lead at the half. Walker scored 23 points -- including 4-for-6 shooting from behind the arc -- in the half to lead the Celtics.

Game notes
Raptors forward Jerome Williams missed his second straight game with a sore left elbow. He is listed as day-to-day and stayed behind in Toronto for treatment. ... Raptors guard Lindsey Hunter missed his sixth straight game with a sore right knee. ... The 32 points scored by the Raptors in the first quarter were the most against the Celtics in the opening period this season. ... The Celtics are 4-0 when Pierce attempts more than 10 free throws in a game. ... Alvin Williams has scored in double figures in 12 straight games.
